Crying out to the world
The marketing campaign Looks Like You Need Iceland has gotten off to a good start, and the cries and calls out in nature are starting to attract people from all over the world.
"You own the joke, I need Iceland," says a woman somewhere out in the big wide world in a comment on the Looks Like You Need Iceland ad campaign on the video-sharing site YouTube.
Another viewer says he will always keep Iceland in his heart forever and a young woman says she will have to go to Iceland as soon as possible, as her boyfriend lives there.
Unfortunately, she is in the United States, and is therefore expecting to have to wait for several more months.
Another spectator asks whether the route to Iceland is passable, since there are no planes.
It is not clear from the story whether he comes from another time zone.
Egill Þórðarson from the advertising agency Peel, who worked on the ads along with the international advertising agency M&C Saatchi, says the response has been far beyond expectations.
I have been involved in many Inspired by Iceland campaigns that have gone very well, but this new campaign is already breaking records.
At its core, this is about creating PR value, that is, getting foreign media to cover the campaign, and it has gone incredibly well.
In a relatively short time, we have received coverage in approximately seven hundred media outlets around the world, which collectively reach over two billion people.
The value of that coverage is estimated at 1.8 billion ISK.
It's not bad at all."
The main market is usually the United States, and the campaign has gone very well there, even though Americans are not expected to visit the country anytime soon.
According to Egill, well-known markets such as Denmark, Britain, and Germany have also done well, as have Russia, which comes as a pleasant surprise.
Then there were responses from foreign areas, such as India, which were not specifically sought out.
"These ads have traveled further than we expected," says Egill, and it is worth noting that over four million people have watched the content on YouTube.
"We couldn't have asked for a better start."
The photos here at the opening were taken by Árni Sæberg, a photographer for Morgunblaðið, during the filming of advertisements with the title "Let It Out" in the middle of last month.
Filming took place all over the place, such as on Skólavörðustíg in Reykjavík, at Reynisfjara, at Skógarfoss, on Sólheimajökull, and in a cave at Hjörleifshöfði.
Directors were Samuel Bjarki Pétursson and Gunnar Páll Ólafsson from Skoti productions, and cinematographer Óttar Guðnason.
In the roles in the aforementioned film, the Icelandic Anna Jia and Murphy Cardenas, who is from Cuba and Hungary, were cast.
Dozens of Icelanders were involved in the making of the ads, while at the same time another group was filming in the south of the country while another group was in the Westfjords and on the West Coast.
According to Egill, "Let It Out" is only the first part of the Looks Like You Need Iceland campaign, with a winter campaign in collaboration with M&C Saatchi planned.
"This is just the first phase of the work for Icelandic Tourist Board," says Egill, adding that the collaboration with M&C Saatchi has gone extremely well.
It's great to work with them.
In such projects, it is very important to have foreign partners with knowledge of the markets we are talking to.
