Bought a boat after tenth grade
"I think we are not many fishermen working in kindergartens across the country," says Axel Örn Guðmundsson, who engages in coastal fishing in the summer but studies psychology at the University of Iceland during the winter.
Coastal fishing is a very convenient summer job when one is in school.
If fishing is good, it is possible to make good money and I think it's great to be able to avoid taking student loans.
The income also helps me get through the winter, too," says Axel Örn Guðmundsson, a 25-year-old psychology student who engages in coastal fishing in the summer, as he has done in previous summers.
Axel was just docking in Tálknafjörð when the reporter caught up with him late in the evening at the beginning of the week.
The winter I was in tenth grade I got my captain's license for boats under twelve meters long, and I bought my boat the summer after I finished elementary school.
I have fished from my boat on the coast every summer since then.
I bought the boat used from a friend of mine, Hartmann Jónsson, and I named it after him.
Hartmann was already an adult when I bought the boat and had stopped going to sea, and he was very happy to see that the boat bore his name.
Hartmann died a few years after I took over the boat," says Axel, adding that he bought the boat for three million.
I made an agreement with Hartmann to pay half, one and a half million, at the beginning of the summer but the other half at the end of the summer when I had finished fishing.
By the end of my first summer on the boat, I owned it debt-free."
But how could a boy have a half a million to pay out in a boat when he had just finished primary school?
I had saved up and put money aside, I had worked with my dad at sea when I was a boy, I fished with him every summer and got my share.
I also put my confirmation money into my boat fund.
Axel was born in Ísafjörður, where all his maternal family is from, but he has lived in Kópavog since he was a boy.
I can fish in the west area because I have a permanent residence with my grandmother in Ísafjörður.
I learned about these areas here in the west from rowing with my dad.
I move between fjords depending on how I feel, as this fishing area covers all of the Westfjords.
Although I prefer to be on the west side, I have also fished around Snæfellsnes and elsewhere.
I have also fished down south, but mostly for herring, says Axel, who always goes out alone very early in the morning and sometimes talks to the seagulls and sings to the sky, spending hours alone on the Baltic Sea.
The internet connection at sea is good, so I can call, listen to podcasts and music.
I don't mind being on my own boat.
Of course, I try to avoid getting into trouble, but there have certainly been times when the weather has been bad, but never any real danger,'' says Axel, who is fortunate that he never gets seasick.
He says the length of the workday depends on how the fishing goes each time.
"In the coastal fishing, I am never more than 14 hours at sea fishing at a time, but I have also fished in other systems, such as the lease quota, and then I have been out at sea continuously for one and a half days fishing."
The arrangement for coastal fishing, he says, is such that he can catch 770 kilos per day, which he finds restrictive.
Other restrictions are that I am not allowed to fish on Fridays, Saturdays, and Sundays, and I am only allowed to fish for twelve days a month, during the four months that the coastal fishing season is in effect, which are May, June, July, and August.
In my opinion, fishermen should choose their fishing days based on the weather and nothing else.
This unnecessary pressure is on people to settle down instead of having 48 days over the whole summer and being able to choose as they please.
The regional division could also be improved in my view, and fishing ports that are well located near fishing grounds should be allowed to benefit from this, says Axel, who mainly catches cod from the sea on his coastal fishing trips, but also some ufsi and other occasional species as well.
Axel works during the winter season with his university studies at the Núpur preschool in Kópavog.
"I think we are not many sailors who work in the country's kindergartens," Axel says proudly, adding that he only intended to work temporarily at the kindergarten.
I got stuck there because I think it's a great job.
I hope that my psychology studies will be useful to me in the future on the preschool level,'' says Axel, who is also well advanced in his studies of business administration.
A registration error prevented homecoming quarantine measures
An error in the form that people fill out when they arrive in the country resulted in a person resident in the country not being called back for a retest.
It is not a requirement to enter a tax ID number if the individual fills out the form in English, as is the case when it is filled out in Icelandic.
"This will be investigated this week," says an expert in infectious diseases at the Chief Medical Officer.
Three domestic infections were detected at the virology department of Landspítalinn yesterday.
One of them that turned out to be positive arrived in the country on July 15, two days after the so-called homecoming quarantine rules came into effect.
Those who are resident in Iceland are then screened upon arrival in the country and then called back for testing four to five days later.
In the midday news on RÚV, it was reported that the individual had, however, followed the old system.
The border screening was negative and he was not called back for testing for the virus.
Camilla Rut Sigfúsdóttir, an expert in the field of public health at the Chief Medical Officer, says in an interview with the newsroom that this can be traced to an error in the electronic registration form.
If people fill out the registration form in English, they do not have to enter a personal identification number as is required in the Icelandic version.
After all, it was primarily intended for foreign tourists.
Therefore, the individual did not receive an automatic invitation to come in for a test.
Kamilla says that many people, however, have followed the rules for homecoming infection routes even though they filled out the registration form in English and in some cases employers have also been vigilant about sending people for testing again after they arrived in the country.
"This week we will look at how we can make it easier for people to access this and draw their attention to the process."
The man is in isolation and six have been put in quarantine.
They all underwent testing, but two were already showing symptoms.
Contact tracing is now underway for the three cases identified yesterday, but it is mostly complete for the two cases reported on Friday.
In both cases, sequencing by Íslensk erfðagreining has revealed that they are variants of the coronavirus that have not been found here before.
In the second case, the focus has been on Israel, even though it is known that the person who brought the virus to the country also traveled to other European countries.
Kamilla says that it should become clear tomorrow where the other virus is coming from.
There are now 15 in isolation according to the website COVID.is.
135 are in quarantine.
Four out of five cases unrelated
Five domestic cases have been detected here in recent days.
Of these, four are completely unrelated and, for example, the source of the infection that occurred at the Rey Cup sports tournament yesterday has not yet been identified.
Contact tracing is still ongoing.
Originally, there were over a dozen individuals who were particularly isolated in quarantine, but this was reduced to sixteen.
In total, 34 are in quarantine due to these new infections that were detected yesterday.
This is the second time in a short period of time that a case has been detected at a sporting event, raising questions about whether such events should be held.
Jóhann K. Jóhannsson, communication officer at the Civil Protection Department of the National Police Commissioner, says it is very easy, as long as people follow guidelines and rules.
We are constantly reminding everyone who lives here that they need to maintain individual protective measures.
We also need to remind people who are organizing events that there are certain rules in place that need to be followed.
Then you can hold events," says Jóhann.
He says that it is possible to prevent infection by maintaining individual-specific infection prevention measures.
In addition, rules and standards are constantly being reviewed.
"What needs to be done, and what the Civil Protection Department and the Office of the Chief Medical Officer are constantly reminding people of, is to pay attention to these individual protective measures.
Both at home and also at service companies.
That people wash their hands and use hand sanitizer.
It prevents the spread of infection," says Jóhann.
We need to remind people that we need to continue on the good path we were on, in order to maintain the success we have achieved so far.
40% of COVID-19 victims had type 2 diabetes
Devon Brumfield heard through the phone how hard her father was having to breathe.
Her father had diabetes, and she encouraged him to seek medical help.
The next day he was let go.
The death was attributed to sudden respiratory difficulties due to a coronavirus infection.
Diabetes was listed on the death certificate as an underlying condition, and Brumfield, who also has diabetes, is terrified that the same fate awaits her.
Reuters news agency says Brumfield's fears are not unfounded.
Figures from a new study commissioned by US authorities show that almost 40% of those who died had type 2 diabetes as an underlying disease.
When the proportion of those who had not yet reached the age of 65 is considered, the percentage rises to half.
The American Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) study covered more than 10,000 people in 15 states who died from the coronavirus between February and May.
Jonathan Wortham, an infectious disease expert at the CDC, says the results are striking, especially for those who have been diagnosed with type 2 diabetes and their loved ones.
Hidden in the slow growth reported by Reuters, a survey was conducted and the answers from the 12 countries that responded indicated similar percentages.
Ten states, including California, Arizona, and Columbia, are not yet reporting underlying diseases.
Diabetes was already an epidemic in slow motion.
Now, COVID-19 has broken through like a powerful tsunami,'' Reuters quotes Elbert Huang, director of the Center for Chronic Disease Research and Policy at the University of Chicago, as saying.
Diabetes is more common among blacks and people of South American origin, who have also fared worse with the coronavirus.
One of the best defenses for those with type 2 diabetes is to keep the disease in check with exercise, a healthy diet, and the help of healthcare professionals.
However, the coronavirus pandemic has made it difficult for many to maintain a routine.
Then, the high price of insulin has forced some to continue going to work and thus risk exposure to the virus.
Reuters points out that U.S. authorities may have been aware of the risk that people with type 2 diabetes could face from the virus.
During the SARS coronavirus outbreak in 2003, about 20% of them had the disease, and during the swine flu pandemic in 2009, this group was three times more likely to require hospitalization.
When MERS made itself known in 2012, one study showed that 60% of those who died or were admitted to intensive care had diabetes.
Charles S. Dela Cruz, a scientist at Yale University, says that because the effects of the COVID-19 virus may last longer, the pandemic has revealed a number of previously unknown side effects.
"I fear we will see a wave of problems when this is over," says Andrew Bolton, Chairman of the International Diabetes Federation.
Doctors have warned that the coronavirus pandemic may indirectly lead to an increase in complications related to diabetes, including kidney disease and kidney failure.
Similarly, new research suggests that the coronavirus may lead to an increase in cases of diabetes.
Reuters says scientists are trying to understand the links between the coronavirus and type 2 diabetes.
The virus attacks the heart, lungs, and kidneys, organs that are already weakened in many people with diabetes.
Then, a high level of glucose and lipids in diabetics can cause a true "cytokine storm," as it is called when the immune system overreacts and attacks the body.
Damaged endothelial cells can also lead to the formation of inflammation, which in turn can cause life-threatening blood clots.
"This is all one big jigsaw puzzle," says Dela Cruz.
"It's all interconnected."
The article has been corrected.
"We were offered champagne, so they left the room"
The couple Ásrún Magnúsdóttir and Atli Bollason accepted the unusual proposition from the artist Ragnar Kjartansson to have sex in front of a camera for a work that the artist was setting up in Paris.
"We loved each other so it wasn't complicated."
Atli Bollason never forgets the moment he met his wife and stepdaughter, Ásrún Magnúsdóttir, for the first time.
I was very attracted to her.
Of course, it was just the radiation, but I also thought it was incredibly cute.
And still does," he says.
Ásrún also remembers this, as her husband regularly recalls the first meeting.
"I am always hearing this story.
Just last weekend," she says, also attracted to her husband at first sight.
I felt and still feel so much excitement around Atli, which I dig.
There's a lot going on and a lot happening and I was drawn to that."
Atli says that the couple emphasized the importance of going their own way in their relationship.
We do not bind our baggage with the same knots as our fellow travelers.
We avoid routines that we recognize around us."
It is perhaps for this reason that they welcomed the presentation from Ragnar Kjartansson, the artist, with open arms, even though it was quite unusual to say the least.
Kristín Anna, our mutual friend, contacts us and asks if we can join her for dessert at Snaps with Ragga and Ingibjörg, Ragnar's wife.
They accepted the invitation, met the trio at Snap's, and had dessert wine and their respective desserts.
They listened to Ragnar as he led them through his plans for an art exhibition he intended to set up at the Palais de Tokyo in Paris in the fall.
He had a multi-part video work called Scenes from Western Culture.
He described it in a simple way."
Ásrún says he described the work as banal and decadent scenes from the daily life of Westerners.
He had sketches of all the scenes he wanted to shoot and last he told us about what he wanted to know if we were interested in participating.
The scene that Ragnar asked the couple to participate in was supposed to show a young middle-class couple falling in love in a minimalist room.
"This is sex with a beginning and an end," says Atli.
The couple didn't know Ragnar very well, although they knew of him and he of them, "but they knew us and thought we fit the bill.
They mentioned that they did not want to advertise for people.
Perhaps they thought they wouldn't get the right people but people who got sexual gratification from performing for others."
They said goodbye to Ragnar and agreed to think about it, but it didn't take long.
When we walked out of Snap, we said: Aren't we just up for this?
It was just like that.
I trust Ragnar as an artist and all his team," says Ásrún and Atli agrees.
"This is about love and closeness"
The scene was filmed in a nice apartment on Mýrargata.
There was a very small film crew there; the cameraman, Ragnar, the sound engineer, and the couple.
After the recording was started, everyone left the room to wait in the car outside except Atli and Ásrún.
We hadn't decided anything about how we were going to be.
We got some minor instructions but we tried to forget time and place.
Being unaware of what we were doing and for whom.
There was no playing involved, we just loved each other so it wasn't complicated," Ásrún says.
But was it romantic?
"Yes, it was a bit romantic," says Atli, and Ásrún agrees.
We were offered champagne before they left the room.
It was like being on vacation at a nice hotel in Paris."
The team was pleased with the performance of the pair in the piece, which moved them.
"When Tommi the cameraman watched this, he cried, he thought it was so beautiful," says Atli.
"This is just as much about love and intimacy as it is about the actual act of intercourse," says Ásrún.
The parents of the couple have seen the work and Atli says that his mother heard the voice in his son at the Reykjavík Art Museum and then realized that he was part of the work.
"Then she turns around and starts thinking about it," says Atli.
Mom and Dad saw this in Paris.
We hadn't told anyone this, but then my dad just sent me a message and said: It was fun to run into the little family at Palais de Tokyo, Ásrún recalls.
And did participation in the project deepen the relationship between Ásrún and Atli?
At least we're still together, so maybe it deepened something.
At least, it deepened my relationship with my in-laws," says Ásrún and laughs.
Ásrún herself saw the work in Copenhagen with her colleague.
"I found it a bit difficult to not be with you, but with someone else," she says, turning to her husband.
But it was fun to see this because it's just one scene in a much larger work, and when you see it with the other works it's very impressive.
I was able to distance myself a little from this and was just proud.
And there was the little bean in my belly," says Ásrún, who was pregnant with the couple's second child when the scene was filmed.
"It was just beautiful."
Anna Marsibil Clausen spoke to Ásrún and Atli on Ástarsögur on Rás 1.
