Without an ambassador for five years since 2009
Jeffrey Gunter Ross, the American ambassador to Iceland, is in the spotlight of the media after CBS reported this morning that he wanted an armed bodyguard because he feared for his life.
However, it has not been a smooth process for the President of the United States to appoint an ambassador here in the country.
Since Carol Van Voorst left the post of U.S. Ambassador in late April 2009, the country has been without an ambassador for a total of 62 months, more than five years.
Van Voorst left office under unusual circumstances, but Kastljós reported in 2009 that she should have received the Order of the Falcon.
On the way to a farewell meeting with the President of Iceland, she received a call from the Presidential Office informing her that she would not be awarded the title.
After leaving Iceland, she taught international relations at the Army War College.
Sixteen months passed before Van Voorst's successor took office, in September 2010.
To some extent, it can be attributed to the fact that Robert S. Connan was appointed as an ambassador but then withdrew.
Finally, Louis Ariega took over the job, having worked in the foreign service for a decade.
He then retired in the fall of 2013 and took up the post of ambassador to Guatemala.
Then came another period without an ambassador, this time lasting for two years.
Robert Barber was approved by the U.S. Congress in January 2015 and took office shortly thereafter, but at that time there had been no ambassador on the ground for 13 months.
Barber was politically appointed but not a diplomat, rather he had worked as a lawyer and supported Barack Obama's election campaign.
He resigned as soon as Donald Trump took office on January 20, 2017, as is customary for politically appointed ambassadors.
Trump's administration was unusually long in appointing both ambassadors and high-ranking officials in the Washington administration.
It took two years for the US Congress to call Jeffrey Ross Gunter to its meeting to question him thoroughly and confirm him as ambassador to Iceland after that.
In his testimony to the court, he said that he had never been to Iceland, but often to Western Europe, while his late wife was of Dutch descent.
Gunter is politically appointed, was previously a dermatologist in California, and has been prominent in the Republican Jewish Coalition, a group of Jewish Republicans.
Casino owner Sheldon Adelson founded the group, and Adelson is a fervent supporter of Donald Trump.
Gunter arrived in Iceland in May 2019, at which point there had been no ambassador in the country since early 2017, for two years and four months, which is the longest period of time without an ambassador that has been seen in Iceland.
The reason is both how long the Trump administration has taken to nominate people to key positions, as well as the fact that the work of the US Congress has dragged on considerably in recent years, including confirming ambassadors to their posts.
Thus, since 2009, Iceland has been without an ambassador for a total of over five years.
However, this has not prevented the embassy from carrying out construction projects, which recently opened its new headquarters at Engjateig.
The construction is estimated to have cost around 6.5 billion, and thick security walls surround the building, while bulletproof glass is in all the windows.
