Pension funds and long shadows
2019 was a big anniversary year in the history of pension funds in Iceland.
Officials had indeed received pensions from the Danish king since the 19th century, but in 1919 a pension fund for civil servants was established, which eventually became the pension fund for all public servants.
The foundation for the current pension schemes for general wage earners was then laid with the all-encompassing collective bargaining agreements on the labor market in 1969, which stipulated occupational pension schemes with compulsory membership and full-fledged fund accumulation from the beginning of 1970.
In 1974, laws were enacted based on these agreements, and the pension system continued to grow after that.
The employees' pension system was not the only radical change that the labor movement of the 20th century achieved through its wage struggle.
Unemployment insurance had been achieved in a similar way during the famous strikes of 1955, and the organization also gradually achieved its demands for sick leave and health insurance, significant vacation rights, shorter working hours, housing improvements, and other such things that were of great importance.
All these rights came at a great cost and with a great struggle, but in retrospect they proved to be a much greater and more lasting gain than the increase in the amount of money in the pay packet, which quickly disappeared in the maw of inflation that characterized the post-war period up until 1990, as many will remember.
The lead-up to the establishment of universal pension funds in 1969 was both long and complex.
Although people eventually came to agree that the funds would ultimately become the property of the fund members, the labor movement had to accept that the boards would be composed of representatives of employers and fund members in equal numbers.
In the years following the establishment of the funds, the demand for a majority of workers in the boards of the funds was often discussed in labour unions, but it never came to fruition, and so we are still left with the abnormal situation where fund members are not in the majority on the boards of the funds.
Section 36 of Act No. 129/1997 on the Mandatory Pension Fund Guarantee and the Operation of Pension Funds deals with the investment policy of the funds.
There, in Article 1, it says that "the pension fund shall have the interests of the members as its guiding principle."
The fifth item also states: "The pension fund shall set ethical guidelines for its investments."
In the shareholder policy of the Efling Trade Union Pension Fund, among other things, the following provisions follow on from the aforementioned legal provisions:
The pension fund is a signatory to the United Nations Principles for Responsible Investment (UN PRI), along with many of the largest pension funds and professional investors in North America and Europe.
The rules discuss how a focus on environmental and social issues, as well as good corporate governance, can contribute to improved investment performance of portfolios.
In this way, the interests of investors and the goals of the society are brought together in a broader context.
LV considers it important that companies, especially those listed on the stock exchange, set public policies on: good corporate governance, fair remuneration, social responsibility and environmental issues.
Gildi, the largest pension fund in the country, has set itself a "policy on responsible investment" and contains provisions of a similar nature.
All of this is revisited here as an introduction to the latest fashion word in Icelandic, "shadow management."
As the term is new in the language, it is not surprising that it has not been fully defined, but I believe the following definition is currently the most widely accepted: Shadow management is when a union leader tells the media that he intends to instruct union representatives on the board of a pension fund to vote a certain way on a particular issue.
If they do not follow the recommendations, they will be removed from the board at the first opportunity.
If the leader does not take this to the media and does not talk about the dismissal, it is not "shadow management" either, since such interactions between people are of course always present in the financial world, just as they are elsewhere.
I leave it to the reader to ponder which path he finds "more sinister."
There are primarily two men who have attempted to shape this definition as of the morning of Saturday, July 25, 2020.
They are Hörður Ægisson, a journalist at Fréttablaðið, and Ásgeir Jónsson, the Central Bank Governor.
The reasons for both were prompted by Bogi Nils Bogason, the CEO of Icelandair, announcing his intention to terminate the company's contracts with flight attendants and stewards (fire them), and Ragnar Þór Ingólfsson, the chairman of the Reykjavík Retailers' Union, sending out instructions to the union's representatives on the board of the Lífeyrissjóður verslunarmanna pension fund to not support the fund's potential acquisition of shares in the company, or they might be dismissed.
A little later, Bogi Nils withdrew his decision and Ragnar Þór followed suit with his recommendations, of course based on Bogi's decision.
Nevertheless, Hörður and Ásgeir saw fit to elaborate on the matter in the Friday edition of Fréttablaðið, using strong words about shadow governance, law-breaking, and the urgent need for changes to the law.
There, a small thistle certainly had to shoulder a heavy burden, though blessed thistle was in a state of suspension and was quickly removed.
Since the matter is important, let's focus on the content itself at the end.
I mentioned earlier the provisions of the Pension Fund Law that relate to this matter.
This entails that the fund managers must look after the interests of the fund members and have ethical considerations in their investments, and these aspects are further elaborated in the regulations of both Gildi and Lífeyrissjóður verslunarmanna, as I mentioned.
Pension funds, however, should NOT solely focus on short-term profitability considerations in their investments.
Such a policy would be extremely dangerous and one does not have to look far back in history to find examples of this, where large loans from banks and funds have flowed to unscrupulous adventurers and environmental disasters, with disastrous consequences.
The CEO of Icelandair was obviously on thin ice when he thought to wipe out an entire group of employees, thus significantly reducing the goodwill the company has enjoyed on the Icelandic market and weakening its position towards investors.
Fortunately, he saw the error of his ways and retracted it.
Time will tell whether this is sufficient to ensure that the pension funds' investment in the company can be considered prudent towards its members in the end.
