A monument to the ephemeral city administration and the owner's and many years' worth of noble intentions that are now back at square one.
When a reporter arrived at Dunhaga 18, he was greeted by open doors and a garbage heap.
A Playstation computer and a recent television lay among other rubbish on the ground - victims of Icelandic summer heat.
The old University Press office was open, and there were a lot of cats there judging by the smell.
It is clear that someone has taken up residence in one corner, but they are not visible.
Stacks of sofas and beds and a few piles of geological pages, presumably intended to become a book, loomed in front of me.
The apartment building's stairways were also open and there was life in both of them.
The reporter was fortunate enough to run into a resident of the other one.
There, the Romanians were cooking a potato dish for dinner and invited the reporter in.
The Romanians work for the staffing agency Ztrongforce ehf.
