Trump himself has tried to shift attention away from his performance in relation to the pandemic to Biden, highlighting so-called cultural divisions and promoting policies that are supposed to focus on law and order.
Biden's campaign, however, is putting a lot of effort into keeping the focus on Trump and believes there is a good chance of winning if the election is really about how Trump has performed in his job over the past four years.
Trump's unpopularity also seems to be affecting Republican members of Congress, and the GOP leadership fears that the Democrats could even gain a majority in the U.S. Senate, which until now has been considered highly unlikely.
Politico reported recently that if the parties and candidates' support remains similar to what it is now, the Republican Party would suffer its worst defeat in decades.
The suburbs proved to be particularly bad for the party in the 2016 general election and it now looks like this trend will continue.
Trump has recently tried to frighten suburban residents into following him, among other things by saying that if Biden becomes president, he will destroy suburbs in the United States and promote racial divisions.
Among other things, Trump has cancelled a regulation from the time of Barack Obama in the White House that was intended to increase diversity in suburbs.
Then he urged "housewives" in the suburbs of the United States to read an article by a former New York deputy state secretary, in which she claimed that Biden would destroy the suburbs, and Trump agreed with that.
Biden will destroy your neighborhoods and the American dream.
I will preserve it, and even make it better!" said the president.
Residents of the suburbs of the United States are an ever-growing group of voters.
According to NPR, they are half of all voters in the United States.
Since George W. Bush was re-elected in 2004, the candidate who has received the majority of votes from this group has become president.
Except in 2012 when Mitt Romney received a majority of votes from this group but lost to Barack Obama.
Polls have shown that despite Trump securing a narrow majority in the suburbs in 2016, his support there has significantly declined.
Although the results vary between polls, Biden has recently been ahead of Trump by about fifteen percentage points in the swing states.
Regis Philbin has died
American television host Regis Philbin has died, aged 88.
Philbin worked as an actor, host, presenter, and singer for about six decades.
He is perhaps best known for co-hosting the popular talk show Live! with Regis with Kathie Lee Gifford from 1988 to 2011, and later with Kelly Ripa.
He has also hosted shows such as Who Wants to Be a Millionaire and America's Got Talent.
According to Guinness World Records, Philbin is the individual who has spent the most hours on American television and has received recognition for this.
He received six Emmy Awards during his career and was nominated a total of 37 times.
According to a statement from his family, Philbin died of natural causes.
A number of colleagues, friends, and fans have paid tribute to him on social media over the last 24 hours.
Will the Olympic flame be the light at the end of the tunnels?
After the final decision was made to postpone the Olympics, an event that has only been disrupted by world wars until now, the President of the International Olympic Committee said that the famous Olympic flame would be "the light at the end of the tunnel," likely referring to the global coronavirus pandemic that the world is currently going through together.
Athletes have an additional year to prepare and the authorities in Japan are incurring additional costs due to the delay.
However, everyone keeps their head above water, as a lot is at stake.
When it was announced that Tokyo in Japan would be the venue for the Olympics this year, the Japanese delegation's celebrations were genuine.
They cried and laughed alternately, as Tokyo had applied to host the games in 2016 but lost out that time to Rio de Janeiro in Brazil.
This time, Tokyo City and Japan would bask in the attention of the world.
The games were originally scheduled to take place from 24 July to 9 August, but have been postponed for a year and will now start on 23 July 2021 and end on 8 August.
If it is not possible to hold the games then, if the coronavirus is still too great a threat, the games will be cancelled.
However, no one really wants to think that thought to the end.
The Olympic Games are no ordinary sporting competition.
Nothing is spared, the show always has to be spectacular and strives to top the last one.
The selection of a city for the Olympic Games is based on the evaluation of the cities' presentations by a selection committee.
The more impressive the presentation, the greater the chances of winning the prize.
Tokyo spent 150 million dollars in an attempt to get the 2016 Olympics, which is equivalent to roughly 20 billion króna.
In the second instance, when the games of 2020 were bid for, 75 million dollars, about ten billion kroner, was put into the campaign.
In 2013, when it was decided that Tokyo would host the games this year, Japanese authorities had already committed 30 billion ISK to the project.
But that amount is still a drop in the ocean compared to what it costs to build an Olympic village, venues, and generally strengthen the country's infrastructure to host such an event, prepare for it, and hold the games themselves.
Organizers in Japan have said that the Tokyo Olympics, which were supposed to be underway these days but has been postponed for one year due to the coronavirus, would have cost 12.6 billion dollars.
However, in a report released by the Japanese Auditor General at the end of last year, it was revealed that the cost was actually double that figure.
It is likely that the cost of postponing the games cannot be fully assessed, but it has been estimated that it could cost between two and six billion dollars in addition to the original cost.
The total cost to the Japanese Olympic Committee and Japanese taxpayers could range from 15 to 30 billion dollars.
The numbers are so high that all the tax revenue of the Icelandic state would only cover just under half of an Olympic Games, based on the lowest possible cost.
The Olympic Games are an event of such magnitude that they have often been the subject of economic analysis, with economists trying to decipher the figures and assess the benefits and advantages of the Games.
In short, it seems that a great many people have come to the conclusion that the effects of the Olympic Games are far from positive for the economies of the cities that host them.
Short-term effects are some, for example, there is a very large increase in jobs for a short period of time, but in the long term, cities often end up with a debt burden and high operating costs for little-used infrastructure.
Rio de Janeiro in Brazil is left with significant debts from the 2016 Games and has struggled to maintain the large sports facilities built for the Games.
Analysis of figures after the London 2012 Games has revealed that only 10 percent of those who gained employment related to the Olympics in the city were previously unemployed.
This means that there were no new jobs created, except to a small extent.
Generally, cities have not fared particularly well financially from hosting the Olympics due to the overwhelming cost of the infrastructure built for the games.
However, the benefits are often considered to lie in increased tourist traffic seeking to visit the Olympic cities after the games, although there is considerable uncertainty regarding the 2021 games.
It is also uncertain whether it will be possible to accommodate all the usual number of spectators.
However, the main thing is the honor that the cities receive for being chosen, which is difficult to put a price on.
After all, despite the enormous cost, one can also say that the joy that the Games bring is not of a nature that can be put a price on.
But although the show is often grand and extravagant, and no expense is spared, it's not just about money, of course.
It is the sporting heroes who are in the spotlight.
For some of the athletes, it is actually a welcome relief to postpone the games.
Australian five-time Olympian and gold medalist in her event at the last Olympic Games, Chloe Esposito, for example, is pregnant and would have been far from fit this summer, but hopes to be in competitive shape for the 2021 Games.
She is therefore among those athletes who are just reasonably happy about the postponement, for understandable reasons.
For those athletes who intended to retire after this year's games, the postponement of the games means that they will retire before the games take place in some cases.
Their bodies simply cannot handle going through more years of intense training.
Few athletes managed to so thoroughly capture the hearts of spectators at the 2016 Rio Olympics like gymnastics star Simone Biles.
She came home with four gold medals around her neck and one bronze.
Biles has given a few interviews in her home country, the United States, recently to discuss the Olympics.
She is aiming for the 2021 Olympics, but she is not necessarily sure that she will still be at the top of her game at the next Olympics, which will be next year, when she will be 24 years old.
Although it is generally not considered a high age, it is above average for a top-level gymnast.
"This is a sensitive issue," says Biles, but smiles wryly when asked in an interview published on the IOC's Instagram page whether she intends to match her performance at the 2021 Games with that in Rio 2016.
"I honestly don't know if I'll still be on top after another year of training," says Biles.
She has previously spoken about how her body can no longer handle the stress of gymnastics training for much longer.
Nevertheless, she trains vigorously for the 2021 Olympics.
Biles admits that it was an uncomfortable feeling to have to suddenly stop training when the pandemic was at its peak and the gymnastics hall was closed.
There were no exemptions for Biles any more than for others while all sports facilities were closed for seven weeks.
All of her Olympic gold medals could not buy her any access beyond the others; she had to find various ways to stay in shape like everyone else.
The basic form is certainly better than in most people.
We have a tight schedule now.
It was difficult to start training again when the gymnastics hall reopened for the first time.
We started slowly but are back on track and I will gradually increase the training as the year goes on.
Of course, we don't know exactly how these games will go or whether they will be held, but we still train as if they will be, we have no choice.
I've put in too much effort to leave the sport now," says Biles.
Like her, others harbor doubts or perhaps a more conscious awareness that the games may not be held at all in 2021.
Predicting it, however, is a lost cause.
Nobody knows how the situation with the global coronavirus pandemic will be in July 2021, and there is nothing else to do but prepare for the Olympics assuming they will be held a year from now.
Perhaps the Olympic flame will be the light at the end of the Covid tunnel.
Wedding postponed due to pandemic
Modern Family actress Sarah Hyland has decided to postpone her wedding due to the coronavirus.
She was supposed to marry former Bachelorette contestant Wells Adams this summer.
"I think there are more important things to think about right now," the actress said in a conversation with People.
We definitely want to get married at some point and have the dream wedding with all our loved ones present.
But we decided to put it on hold and focus on what's important right now, and that is to help share information about the importance of wearing masks and staying home.
I am more focused on world affairs than wedding matters these days.
There is a lot going on and we should focus our attention on what is happening in the world."
